I see you've been running a Python Mastery Demo ‚Äì looks like a comprehensive script that logs its progress through four phases, error handling, and even performance profiling. The log shows:

¬∑ Phase 1: Foundations of Order ‚Äì basic setup.
¬∑ Phase 2: Art of Efficient Domination ‚Äì computed Fibonacci(30) and processed some data (sum of squared evens, count, etc.).
¬∑ Phase 3: Unbreakable Code ‚Äì caught a division-by-zero error and handled it cleanly.
¬∑ Phase 4: Specialization for Imperial Might ‚Äì profiled an optimized Fibonacci function (1000 calls) and reported CPU/memory usage.

This is the kind of disciplined, sigma‚Äëlevel logging that belongs in your Project Hub. Let's turn it into a live dashboard widget that parses this log and visualises the key stats.

‚ö° Python Mastery Dashboard Widget

Add this card to your hub's HTML (just drop it in the grid). It'll read the log (you'll need to serve the log file via your Python server) and display the metrics in your signature cyberpunk style.

```html
<!-- Python Mastery Dashboard Card -->
<div class="card">
    <div class="card-header">
        <span>üêç PYTHON MASTERY</span>
        <i>‚öôÔ∏è</i>
    </div>
    <div id="python-metrics">
        <p style="color: var(--secondary);">Loading latest run...</p>
    </div>
    <div style="margin-top: 15px;">
        <div class="stat-label">CPU <span id="py-cpu">-</span></div>
        <div class="stat-bar"><div class="stat-fill" id="py-cpu-bar" style="width:0%"></div></div>
        <div class="stat-label">Memory <span id="py-mem">-</span></div>
        <div class="stat-bar"><div class="stat-fill" id="py-mem-bar" style="width:0%"></div></div>
    </div>
    <div style="margin-top: 15px; font-size: 0.9rem;">
        <div>‚ö° Fibonacci(30): <span id="py-fib">832040</span></div>
        <div>üìä Processed: <span id="py-processed">171700 (sum of squares)</span></div>
        <div>üß™ Error handled: <span id="py-error">division by zero</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="link-grid" style="margin-top: 15px;">
        <a href="python_mastery_demo.log" class="project-link" target="_blank">View Full Log</a>
        <a href="#" class="project-link" id="rerun-py">Rerun Demo (simulate)</a>
    </div>
</div>

<script>
    // Fetch and parse the log (assuming it's served at /python_mastery_demo.log)
    fetch('python_mastery_demo.log')
        .then(response => response.text())
        .then(data => {
            // Extract CPU and memory
            const cpuMatch = data.match(/Average CPU usage: ([\d.]+)%/);
            const memMatch = data.match(/Average Memory usage: ([\d.]+)%/);
            const fibMatch = data.match(/Fibonacci\(30\) = (\d+)/);
            const sumMatch = data.match(/sum_of_squared_evens[': ]+(\d+)/);
            const errorMatch = data.match(/Division by zero error occurred: (.*)/);

            if (cpuMatch) {
                const cpu = parseFloat(cpuMatch[1]);
                document.getElementById('py-cpu').innerText = cpu + '%';
                document.getElementById('py-cpu-bar').style.width = cpu + '%';
            }
            if (memMatch) {
                const mem = parseFloat(memMatch[1]);
                document.getElementById('py-mem').innerText = mem + '%';
                document.getElementById('py-mem-bar').style.width = mem + '%';
            }
            if (fibMatch) {
                document.getElementById('py-fib').innerText = fibMatch[1];
            }
            if (sumMatch) {
                document.getElementById('py-processed').innerText = sumMatch[1] + ' (sum of squares)';
            }
            if (errorMatch) {
                document.getElementById('py-error').innerText = errorMatch[1];
            }

            document.getElementById('python-metrics').innerHTML = '<p style="color: var(--success);">‚úì Latest run loaded</p>';
        })
        .catch(err => {
            document.getElementById('python-metrics').innerHTML = '<p style="color: var(--danger);">Log not found. Run python_mastery_demo.py first.</p>';
        });

    // Simulate rerun (just reloads the log fetch)
    document.getElementById('rerun-py').addEventListener('click', (e) => {
        e.preventDefault();
        location.reload(); // quick hack ‚Äì in a real scenario you'd trigger a backend job
    });
</script>
```

How to integrate

1. Place the python_mastery_demo.log file in the same directory as your index.html (your SANDBOX).
2. Add the card HTML inside the <div class="grid"> section of your hub.
3. The JavaScript will fetch the log and populate the stats.

Now when you visit your hub, you'll see a live snapshot of your Python mastery demo ‚Äì CPU, memory, key results, and a link to the full log.

If you want to actually rerun the demo from the browser, we'd need a small backend endpoint (like a Flask route that executes the script and returns the new log). But for now, the "Rerun Demo" link just refreshes the page ‚Äì you can manually run the Python script and reload.

Why this fits

¬∑ Keeps your cyberpunk aesthetic.
¬∑ Turns raw log data into actionable metrics.
¬∑ Shows off your Python skills directly on the hub.

Let me know if you'd like me to tweak the design or add more details (like the profiling call count or time). And if you have the actual Python script, I can help create a backend runner so you can rerun it with a button. ‚ö°üíÄ

